<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="573" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="573">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="573">Discussion.</emphasis>
The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Shi &amp; Zheng, 1996" authorityName="Shi &amp; Zheng" authorityYear="1996" box="[672,1279,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Xizicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="573" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biprocerus" subGenus="Paraxizicus">
<emphasis box="[672,753,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="573">Xizicus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[769,901,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="573">Paraxizicus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[918,1038,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="573">biprocerus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shi" box="[1053,1270,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="573" refString="Shi, F. M. &amp; Zheng, Z. M. (1996) Description of a new species of the genus Xiphidiopsis from China (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Meconematinae). Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica, 32 (3), 332 - 334." type="journal article" year="1996">Shi &amp; Zheng, 1996</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
by: processes of male tenth abdominal tergite dorso-ventrally expanded, apex of each process divided into two compressed branches; the middle area in the midline of ventral surface of subgenital plate longitudinally broadly raised ventrally, the apex with a pair of stout spines; subapices of lateral margins of subgenital plate slightly expanded, with a pair of thin spines directing posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1435,404,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="573" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,464]" box="[199,1435,404,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="573">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,404,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="573">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new species is derived from the morphology of the male tenth abdominal tergite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
